{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}
'''Iorwerth Peate''', also known as '''Cyfeiliog''', (27 February 1901 – 19 October 1982) was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] [[poet]] and scholar, best known as the founder, along with [[Cyril Fox]], of [[St Fagans National History Museum]]. Born in [[Llanbrynmair]] into a family of carpenters, his interest in folk studies and anthropology was kindled when studying Colonial History and Geography at [[Aberystwyth University]] under professor [[Herbert John Fleure]] and writer [[Thomas Gwynn Jones|T. Gwynn Jones]].<ref>''The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales''. [[John Davies (historian)|John Davies]], [[Nigel Jenkins]], Menna Baines and Peredur Lynch (2008) pg656 {{ISBN|978-0-7083-1953-6}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/story-wales-best-loved-museum-14981627|title=The story of Wales' best-loved museum as St Fagans hits 70|last=Clements|first=Laura|date=2018-08-04|work=walesonline|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref> Peate received an M.A. in 1924 for a dissertation on the anthropology, dialect and folklore of the people living in the [[Dyfi hills|Dyfi valley]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s6-PEAT-CYF-1901.html|title=The National Library of Wales :: Dictionary of Welsh Biography|website=yba.llgc.org.uk|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref> While studying at Aberystwyth, Peate won university prizes for his poetry and for his participation in the [[eisteddfod]].<ref name=":1" />

Peate began his career by lecturing in rural [[Ceredigion]] and [[Merionethshire|Meirioneth]], before being appointed in 1927 to catalogue the [[National Museum of Wales]]' folk collections.<ref name=":1" />

Inspired by the open-air museums of Scandinavia, Peate had a vision of recreating this style of attraction, but for Welsh life and culture.<ref name=":0" /> His initial attempts were challenged by those outside and inside the academic world. The work on the museum commenced in 1946, thanks to the donation of land from the [[Earl of Plymouth]].

Peate published work on the study of folk life in both [[English language|English]] and [[Welsh language|Welsh]]. He was a pacifist who registered as a [[conscientious objector]] in 1941 and believed in a monoglot Welsh-speaking Wales.<ref name=":1" />

Peate was a judge for the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales|National Eisteddfod]] for a number of years.<ref name=":1" /> 

Peate received a number of honours over his life. He was awarded an [[Honorary degree|honourary doctorate]] by both the [[National University of Ireland]] and the [[University of Wales]].<ref name=":1" /> He declined a 1963 New Years honour appointment as an Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (OBE).{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}

Peate, along with his wife, is buried in the Unitarian chapel on the grounds of St Fagans National History Museum.<ref name=":1" /> 

==Published works==
* ''Canu Chwarter Canrif'' (1957)

