{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> |name = Yechiel Granatstein |birth_date = {{Birth date|1913|6|6|mf=y}} |birth_place= [[Lublin]], [[Poland]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|2008|2|7|1913|6|6|mf=y}} |death_place= [[Israel]] |occupation = Novelist, biographer, short story writer |language = [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], [[Hebrew]] |citizenship = Israel |notableworks = The War of a Jewish Partisan; One Jew's Power, One Jew's Glory }}
'''Yechiel Granatstein''' ({{lang-he|יחיאל גראנאטשטיין}}; June 6, 1913 – February 7, 2008) was a [[Poland|Polish]]-born [[Jewish]] author and writer in [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]] and [[Hebrew]], as well as a partisan fighter in World War II and a [[Jewish refugee]] activist following the [[Holocaust]].
==Life== Yechiel Granatstein was born in [[Lublin]], Poland on June 6, 1913. Even before [[World War II]], he had developed his skills as a writer, writing for Dos Yiddish Tagblat and various [[World Agudath Israel|Agudah]] periodicals. While still young and single, he was drafted into the Polish army for military training. He lived in [[Łódź]] in 1936-1939. Following the Nazi-Soviet [[invasion of Poland]] at the outbreak of World War II he escaped from the Germans to [[Slonim]], which was on the Russian side of the [[Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact|Molotov–Ribbentrop line]], eventually entrapped in the [[Słonim Ghetto]] after [[Operation Barbarossa]].<ref name="PL198">{{cite book |title=Holocaust: The Nazi Persecution and Murder of the Jews |author=Peter Longerich |publisher=OUP Oxford |year=2010 |ISBN=0192804367 |pages=198, 238, 347 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=cxYqYIn73SgC&q=Slonim}}</ref> {{see also|Jewish ghettos in German-occupied Poland}}
In 1942 he escaped to the nearby forests and joined the partisans that were fighting the Nazis. He was accepted into the partisan unit because of his earlier training as a soldier and because he possessed an automatic machine gun. After the war he returned to Łódź where he assisted refugees in leaving Europe from his base at 66 Wschodnia Street and then continued his refugee rescue work in [[Paris]] from 1946-1950. It was in Paris in 1950 that he published an [[autobiography]] of his time fighting as a Jewish partisan under the title "I Wanted to Live" (Ich hob gevolt lebn" in Yiddish), which detailed the dangers he faced not just from the German Nazis, but from his fellow Russian partisans as well. This book was translated into Hebrew and in English under the title "The War of a Jewish Partisan". He immigrated to [[Israel]] in the 1950s where he continued to write about pre-war Europe and the Holocaust. In Israel he wrote for "Shearim", "[[Hamodia]]", "[[HaTzofe]]" and other newspapers and journals. He also wrote a biography about his father-in-law's, the Radoschitzer Rebbe's, experiences in the ghettos and [[concentration camps]]. He died February 7, 2008 in Israel.
==Published works== * איך האָב געוואָלט לעבן (English: I Want to Live) (א"ב צעראטא, Paris, 1950) ** Translated to Hebrew by Naftoli Ginton and published as יהודי ביער (English: A Jew in the Forest) (מורשת, Tel Aviv, 1955) ** Translated to Hebrew by the author as יהודי ביער: קורותיו של פרטיזן יהודי (English: A Jew in the Forest: The Experiences of a Jewish Partisan) (מאור, Tel Aviv, 1983) ** Translated to English by Charles Wengrov as The War of a Jewish Partisan: A Youth Imperiled by his Russian Comrades and Nazi Conquerors ([[ArtScroll|Mesorah]], Brooklyn, 1986, {{ISBN|0-89906-477-9}}) * אורות מאופל (English: Blackened Lights) (קרית ספר, Jerusalem, 1958) * לכסיקון הגבורה (with משה כהנוביץ) ([[Yad Vashem]], Jerusalem, 1965-1968) * שמש בענן (English: Sun in the Cloud) ([[Mossad Harav Kook]], Jerusalem, 1975) * פרעמדע וועלדער - אייגענע ערד (English: Strange Forest - Familiar Land) (פארלאג י"ל פרץ, Tel Aviv, 1979) * שלכת באביב: סיפורים קצרים (English: Autumn in the Spring: Short Stories) (סיפן, Jerusalem, 1980) * תלמידי הבעל-שם-טוב בארץ ישראל: למעלה ממאתיים שנה לעליית תלמידיהם של הבעש"ט ושל המגיד ממזריץ לארץ ישראל (English: The Students of the [[Baal Shem Tov]] in Israel) (מאור, Tel Aviv, 1982) * ארץ-ישראל של מעלה: עלייתם של גדולי ישראל לארץ ישראל (English: Heavenly Land of Israel: The Ascent of Sages of Israel to the Land of Israel) (פאר, Tel Aviv, 1985) * השביל והדרך: על הצדיק רבי שמואל מקוריב, מהחבריא הקדושה של הרב ר' אלימלך מליזנסק וה"חוזה" מלובלין ועל תלמידיו (English: The Path and the Road: About the [[Tzadik]] Rabbi Shmuel from Koriv) (פאר, Bnei Brak, 1986) * הוד וגבורה: האדמו״ר מראדושיץ בפיוטרקוב רבי יצחק שמואל אליהו פינקלר הי״ד, חייו וקורותיו בגיטו ובמחנותf (מכון זכר נפתלי, Jerusalem, 1987) ** Translated to English by Charles Wengrov as One Jew's Power One Jew's Glory: The Life of Rav Yitzchak Shmuel Eliyahu Finkler, the Rebbe of Radoschitz, in the Ghetto and Concentration Camps (Feldheim Publishers, 1991, {{ISBN|978-0873065597}}) * הגבורה האחרת : היהודי הדתי במאבק גבורה ובמרי נגד גזירות הנאצים בשנות השואה (ירושלים : מכון זכר נפתלי, תשמ"ט 1989) * חיים כפולים (ירושלים : פאר, תשנ"א 1991) * מגע בנפש (ירושלים : פאר, תשנ"ד 1993) <רומן> * הולכי נתיבות (ירושלים : פאר, תשנ"ה 1995) * ימי בראשית : סיפורה המופלא של ההחייאה הרוחנית-אמונתית-דתית למחרת השואה ע"י קומץ ניצולים חרדיים (בני ברק, תשנ"ז 1996) * שם נפשו בחיים (בני ברק : פאר, תשנ"ח 1998)
